content.description: A stressfully fun and steep route that gets better with good kneebars.
content.location: Across from Doorf, and in the middle of two other bolt lines.

content.description: A good route that needs to be climbed more. Get ready for monkey business and a one armed swing. Be sure to pre-place or stick clip the draw on the roof. The clip is more than likely impossible on the go.
content.location: Opposite of Doorf and to the left of two other bolt lines.

content.description: On the wall, just opposite of Doorf, sits and overhung jungle gym filled with holds that would be better if God had arranged them differently. Use em' right and a hella fun challenge awaits the five thirteen climber who likes a short, hella-overhung haul from the tiny hold whorehouses of the old country.
content.location: Across from Doorf and to the left of two other bolt lines.

content.description: Climbing through the first three bolts is the easiest portion of the route. Starts directly under first bolt and follows the big pockets up and to the right. The crux of the route is from the third bolt to the roof. Climb the chalked crimps and sidepulls to the base of the roof. Awesome bolt placements. Super protected. Great warm up route.
content.location: From the top of the trail where it meets with old gravel road, go left and follow trail along pipeline into shallow corridor. When you walk up the mineshaft door it is the route to the left.

content.description: The Tunnel Wall is a small area that holds a handful of routes ranging from the great warmup, Doorf 5.9, to some burly steep climbs like Stress Test 5.12a and French Pinchler 5.13b.    The area can be quite cool due to a constant breeze from the tunnel.
